\begin_layout Abstract
The fluctuation-dissipation relation, a central result in non-equilibrium
 statistical physics, relates equilibrium fluctuations in a system to its
 linear response to external forces.
 Here we provide a direct experimental verification of this relation for
 viscously coupled oscillators, as realized by a pair of optically trapped
 colloidal particles.
 A theoretical analysis, in which interactions mediated by slow viscous
 flow are represented by non-local friction tensors, matches experimental
 results and reveals a frequency maximum in the amplitude of the mutual
 response which is a sensitive function of the trap stiffnesses and the
 friction tensors.
 This allows for its location and width to be tuned and suggests the utility
 of the trap setup for accurate two-point microrheology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relation between the generalized susceptibility and equilibrium fluctuations
 of the generalized forces, first obtained for a linear resistive circuit
 by Nyquist 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nyquist1928thermal"

\end_inset

 and then proved for any general linear dissipative system by Callen and
 Welton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "callen1951"

\end_inset

, is a central result in non-equilibrium statistical physics.
 The relation can be used to infer the intrinsic fluctuations of a system
 from measurements of its response to external perturbations or, perhaps
 more startlingly, to predict its response to external perturbations from
 the character of its intrinsic fluctuations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kubo1966fluctuation"

\end_inset

.
 The fluctuation-dissipation relation is the point of departure for several
 areas of current research including fluctuation relations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "seifert2012stochastic"

\end_inset

, relaxation in glasses 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "berthier2011theoretical"

\end_inset

, and response and correlations in active 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "fodor2016far"

\end_inset

 and driven systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "mason95,levine2000"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first experimental
\emph on
 
\emph default
verification of the relation between fluctuation and dissipation was due
 to Johnson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "johnson1928thermal"

\end_inset

, whose investigation of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

thermal agitation of electricity in conductors
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 provided the motivation for Nyquist's theoretical work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nyquist1928thermal"

\end_inset

.
 Though the relation has been verified since in systems with conservative
 couplings, a direct verification in a system where the coupling is entirely
 dissipative is, to the best of our knowledge, not available.
 Colloidal particles in a viscous fluid interact through velocity-dependent
 many-body hydrodynamic forces whose strength, away from boundaries, is
 inversely proportional to the distance between the particles.
 The range of these dissipative forces can be made much greater than that
 of conservative forces such as the DLVO interaction 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "derjaguin1941theory,verwey1948"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, it is possible to engineer a situation where the dominant coupling
 between colloidal particles is the viscous hydrodynamic force and all other
 interactions are negligibly small.
 Such systems, then, are ideal for testing the fluctuation-dissipation relation
 when couplings are purely dissipative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this Letter, we present a direct verification of the fluctuation-dissipation
 relation for a pair of optically trapped colloidal particles in water.
 We measure the equilibrium fluctuations of the distance between the particles
 and the response of one particle to the sinusoidal motion of another particle.
 Transforming both correlations and responses to the frequency domain, we
 verify the fluctuation-dissipation relation over a range of frequencies
 spanning two orders of magnitude.
 Remarkably, the response function has a peak in frequency, reminiscent
 of a resonance, though the system of oscillators is entirely overdamped.
 A theoretical analysis, assuming slow viscous flow of the ambient water,
 is in excellent agreement with the experiments.
 The analysis reveals that the location and width of the resonant peak can
 be tuned by altering the viscosity, the separation between the particles,
 the trap stiffnesses, and the colloidal diameters.
 It provides the inverse relations necessary for using the trap setup for
 accurate two-point microrheology.
 We now present details of our experiment and its analysis.
