\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Theory:
\shape default
 The Langevin equations describing the stochastic trajectories of the colloids
 are 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gardiner1985handbook"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
m_{i}\dot{\boldsymbol{v}_{i}} & +\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}\cdot\boldsymbol{v}_{j}+{\bf \boldsymbol{\nabla}}_{i}U=\boldsymbol{{\bf \xi}}_{i},\label{eq1}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j=1,2$
\end_inset

 refer to the driving and driven colloid, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{i}$
\end_inset

 are their masses, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are their velocities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 are the second-rank friction tensors encoding the velocity-dependent dissipativ
e forces mediated by the fluid, 
\begin_inset Formula $U=U_{1}+U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the total potential of the conservative forces, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\xi}_{i}$
\end_inset

, the Langevin noises, are zero-mean Gaussian random variables whose variance
 is provided by the fluctuation-dissipation relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\boldsymbol{\xi}_{i}(t)\boldsymbol{\xi}_{j}(t^{\prime})\rangle=2k_{B}T\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}\delta(t-t^{\prime})$
\end_inset

.
 The bold-face notation, with Cartesian indices suppressed, is used for
 both vectors and tensors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the limit of slow viscous flow in the fluid, the friction tensors can
 be calculated from the Stokes equation using a variety of methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ladd1988,mazur1982,cichocki1994friction,singh2016crystallization,singh2016traction"

\end_inset

.
 To leading order the result is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\gamma}_{ij}=\delta_{ij}\boldsymbol{I}\gamma_{i}-(1-\delta_{ij})\gamma_{i}\gamma_{j}\mathcal{F}_{i}\mathcal{F}_{j}\boldsymbol{G}(\boldsymbol{r}_{i},\boldsymbol{r}_{j}),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{i}=6\pi\eta a_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the self-frictions, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{G}$
\end_inset

 is a Green's function of the Stokes equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pozrikidis1992"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the centers of the colloids and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}_{i}=1+\frac{a_{i}^{2}}{6}\nabla_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are the Faxén corrections that account for the finite radius, 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

, of the colloids.
 We emphasize that this expression is not limited to the translationally
 invariant Green's function of unbounded flow, 
\begin_inset Formula $8\pi\eta\,\boldsymbol{G}(\boldsymbol{r})=(\nabla^{2}\boldsymbol{I}-\boldsymbol{\nabla\nabla})r$
\end_inset

, but holds generally for any Green's function and is both symmetric and
 positive-definite 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "singh2016crystallization,singh2016traction"

\end_inset

.
 The mutual friction tensors decay inversely with distance in an unbounded
 fluid and more rapidly in the proximity of boundaries.
 The assumption of slow viscous flow is valid at frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\tau_{\nu}\ll1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{\nu}=\rho L^{2}/\eta$
\end_inset

 is the vorticity diffusion time scale 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kim2005"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The harmonic optical potentials are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{i}(t)=\frac{1}{2}k_{i}|{\bf \boldsymbol{r}}_{i}-{\bf \boldsymbol{r}}_{i}^{0}|^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 are the centers and 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the stiffnesses of the optical traps.
 Note the absence of conservative mutual couplings.
 The system remains in equilibrium when the trap centers are stationary
 but is driven into non-equilibrium when they are modulated in time as 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r}_{i}^{0}(t)$
\end_inset

.
 For small modulations the response is linear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For modulation frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\ll\gamma_{i}/m_{i}$
\end_inset

 the velocities can be adiabatically eliminated from the inertial Langevin
 equations to yield inertialess Langevin equations for the positions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gardiner1984adiabatic"

\end_inset

.
 The multiplicative noises in the resulting equations have clear interpretations
 within the adiabatic elimination procedure; there is no Itô-Stratonovich
 dilemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "van1981ito,gardiner1985handbook,van1992stochastic,klimontovich1990ito,klimontovich1994nonlinear"

\end_inset

.
 Both correlation and response functions can be calculated in this limit.
 Linearizing about the mean separation between the trap centers and decomposing
 the motion into components parallel and perpendicular to the separation
 vector, the result for the parallel response function is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\text{Im}\left[\chi_{ij}^{||}(\omega)\right]=\frac{\omega M_{ij}}{(\text{det}A-\omega^{2})^{2}+(\omega\begin{tabular}{c}
 tr\end{tabular}A)^{2}},
\end{gather}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{ij}=\mu_{ij}^{||}k_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

response
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 matrix, the mobility matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{ij}^{||}$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the friction matrix and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{ij}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\begin{tabular}{c}
 \tfrac{k_{2}}{k_{1}}\mu_{22}^{\parallel}\end{tabular}\text{det}A+\mu_{11}^{\parallel}\omega^{2} & -\mu_{12}^{\parallel}(\text{det}A-\omega^{2})\\
\, & \,\\
-\mu_{21}^{\parallel}(\text{det}A-\omega^{2}) & \begin{tabular}{c}
 \tfrac{k_{1}}{k_{2}}\mu_{11}^{\parallel}\end{tabular}\text{det}A+\mu_{22}^{\parallel}\omega^{2}
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset

The magnitude of the response of the driven bead to the driving bead is
 maximum at the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

resonance
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 frequency
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{res}=\sqrt{\text{det}A}=\sqrt{\mu_{11}^{\parallel}\mu_{22}^{\parallel}k_{1}k_{2}\left(1-\frac{\mu_{12}^{\parallel}\mu_{21}^{\parallel}}{\mu_{11}^{\parallel}\mu_{22}^{\parallel}}\right)}.\label{eq4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

A simple analysis of the system with the two particles executing Brownian
 motion in the absence of the external drive leads us to write down the
 auto and cross-correlation functions (
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}$
\end_inset

), so that by comparing with the response functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{Im}(\chi_{ij}^{\parallel})$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{ij}=(k_{B}T/\pi f)\,\text{Im}(\chi_{ij}^{\parallel})$
\end_inset

 which is the well known fluctuation-dissipation relationship 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kubo1966fluctuation"

\end_inset

.
